{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T22-29-33-169Z","slug":"semantic-vector-search-landscape","locale":"ru","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T22:29:41.967Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-01--semantic-vector-search-landscape/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-01--semantic-vector-search-landscape/ru/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/semantic-vector-search-landscape/ru/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T22-29-33-169Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"572f632a4fafd980b89c8a3904ef4f531468c50aac3fa5a9debce113dd6202a8","outputHash":"3128b6efbfb01cc35b324600ba65be16b62aaabbbe214354ce96675db955dbaf","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that semantic (vector) search is a complementary layer—not a universal replacement—for traditional lexical, fuzzy, and exact‑match techniques. It explains how embeddings turn text (or other media) into high‑dimensional vectors, how similarity is measured (e.g., via HNSW indexes), and why this enables meaning‑based retrieval such as cross‑language matches, intent‑driven queries, and nearest‑neighbor recommendations. The piece outlines concrete scenarios where pgvector (Postgres‑based vector search) shines—RAG pipelines, intent‑driven article lookup, similarity‑based deduplication, and multilingual search—while warning that vectors must be combined with lexical results (using methods like RRF) and filtered by similarity thresholds to avoid low‑confidence matches. The tone is a practical tutorial aimed at engineers and product teams responsible for building search‑oriented systems, using the metaphor of a “hybrid architecture” where each tool occupies its proper niche.","totalInputTokens":15383,"totalOutputTokens":8436,"totalCacheReadTokens":6144,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":7413,"totalCostUsd":0.002118417,"pricingSource":"local-openro