{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-13T23-30-09-223Z","slug":"semantic-vector-search-landscape","locale":"he","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-13T23:30:35.250Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-01--semantic-vector-search-landscape/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-05-01--semantic-vector-search-landscape/he/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/semantic-vector-search-landscape/he/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-13T23-30-09-223Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"572f632a4fafd980b89c8a3904ef4f531468c50aac3fa5a9debce113dd6202a8","outputHash":"a899ff57b8c39162c6234ac35dd5e89c527b2d20593df4aadba230d5e96a0034","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that semantic (vector) searchis a complementary layer—not a universal replacement—for traditional lexical, fuzzy, and exact‑match techniques. It explains how embeddings turn text (or other media) into high‑dimensional vectors, how similarity is measured (e.g., via HNSW indexes), and why this enables meaning‑based retrieval such as cross‑language matches, intent‑driven queries, and nearest‑neighbor use cases (RAG, deduplication, recommendation). The piece stresses a hybrid architecture: use pgvector (or similar) alongside Postgres full‑text search, BM25, and trigram/fuzzy tools, and combine results with methods like Reciprocal Rank Fusion. The tone is a practical tutorial aimed at engineers and architects who design search systems and need to decide when to employ vector search versus classic FTS. Recurring metaphors frame search as “different tools in a toolbox” and describe vectors as “points in a high‑dimensional space” whose proximity encodes semantic similarity.","totalInputTokens":15926,"totalOutputTokens":8892,"totalCacheReadTokens":5120,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":24724,"totalCostUsd":0.002221674,"pricingSource":"local-openr